{"solution":"Use an augment-style versioning decorator on the specific spread-in property so that the identity envelope only appears starting from `2025-05-04-preview`, while keeping your resource model definition unchanged.

Conceptually, if your resource is:

```typespec
model MyResource is TrackedResource<MyResourceProperties> {
  ...ResourceNameParameter<MyResource>;
  ...Azure.ResourceManager.ManagedServiceIdentityProperty;
}
```

you should add an `@@added` (augment) decorator scoped to the `identity` property that the spread model contributes, targeting the first API version that should expose MSI. For example:

```typespec
// Assuming your version enum contains 2025-05-04-preview, e.g.:
// enum Versions {
//   v2023_01_01,
//   v2024_06_01,
//   v2025_05_04_preview,
// }

model MyResource is TrackedResource<MyResourceProperties> {
  ...ResourceNameParameter<MyResource>;
  ...Azure.ResourceManager.ManagedServiceIdentityProperty;
}

// Version gate the spread-in identity property so it is
// only present starting from 2025-05-04-preview
@@added(MyResource.identity, Versions.v2025_05_04_preview);
```

Key points:
- You do NOT change the spread itself (`...ManagedServiceIdentityProperty`) and you keep the resource structure intact.
- `@@added` is an augment decorator that targets a specific member on an existing model (here `MyResource.identity`) and introduces that member only from the given version onward.
